tion for the early church’s sometimes harsh attitude was partly theological—it needed to define itself over against its parent—and partly sociological—it needed to make clear the line that divided the fledgling group of Christian believers fromt he group with which it was most likely to be confused. This collection of studies emphasizes the context and history of early Christianity in reconsidering many of the classic passages that have contributed to the development of anti-Judaism in Christianity. The volume opens with an essay that clearly delineates the state of the question of anti-Judaism in early Christianity. Then follow discussions of specific passages in the writings of Paul as well as the Gospels.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristianity and other religionsxJudaism. 0aChurch historyxPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aChurch historyyPrimitive and early church, ca. 30-600. 0aJudaismxRelationsxChristianity. 4aReligion. 7aRELIGION / Biblical Studies / New Testament.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Charles P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuck, Erwin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFraikin, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaston, Lloyd, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGranskou, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGranskou, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHurd, John C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKlassen, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrzybylski, Benno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRichardson, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabu